>>114868154
I feel it's more of an aesthetic game than anything. Plenty of "blackgaze" and "black metal" music share a lot of qualities of shoegaze, but are mostly disregarded as completely different (black metal) or as its own thing (black gaze). Early Alcest and Trautonist seem to be more of shoegaze, but are considered "black gaze". What? I am convinced it's all in the marketing and image, same thing with slowcore. Slowcorers look more like shoegazers, and as far as i'm aware, social media and the internet has pushed both these genres to a higher combined forefront. it makes sense..... dream pop, shoegaze and slowcore are more prettier music. black gaze is a silly thing, not entirely shoegaze and not entirely black metal. it just seems like "metal" or "pretty rock" , a lot of it to me it does. Deafheaven has a fancy pedalboard, a well-rounded drummer who can play patterns, and a gay dancing singer, but to me are neither shoegaze or black metal. It's just.... pretty music? what? they dress either suave or normally but what are they made out to be? BLACK METAL?? are you kidding me! It just confuses me how people choose which band goes into what folder on their computer.
lovesliescrushing is said to be like "mbv"... no? this is ambiance, not shoegaze. what is slowcore? slow dream-pop? that's kind of like shoegaze, and they dress more similar to shoegazers, kinda. I don't get it.

>>114889721
That's true and it's one of the main reasons I don't usually listen to video game music even if I like the tracks ingame. The standards for what is good video game music are just different than the standards for good "regular" music, since if it's any good it's designed to be part of a specific experience. In this way, music that's very mediocre when listened to in isolation can still have a strong effect when it's used ingame.

Maybe the ultimate example of this (at least from games I've played) is Metal Gear Rising. If someone says they unironically listen to the game's OST I find it very hard to take them seriously because it's really just not good, but when you hear the tracks ingame the whole thing is taken to the next level because it perfectly fits the silly+edgy atmosphere of the game and enhances the impact of the action happening on-screen. Something similar is true with the Doom 2016 OST. I can't imagine anyone listening to for example Mastermind for fun, but ingame you can practically feel the rhythm of the fight in the music and the combination enhances both the action and the music.

An even more extreme version of this happens in Bravely Default. If you listen to Serpent Devouring the Horizon, you miss the massive significance that every element of the track has within the game. The whole track is like a puzzle where the pieces have been laid out during the game and they finally come together at the final boss, but even if it's explained it doesn't have any real impact unless you've experienced the game and have made the mental connections to the music that this track is designed to trigger. It's a masterful use of music but it's meaningless outside of its intended context.

I'm not saying video games can't have music that has merit on its own, but for me GOOD video game music isn't just a good track that happens to be used in a game, it's a track that enchances and is enhanced by the game and thus needs to be experienced in that context.

History tells the story. There are only 3 contenders. Zeppelin IV, Beatles Revolver, and Stones Exile.

A handful of outliers would insist on a Dylan contender, maybe Hwy 61 or Blood On The Tracks, but Dylan's albums time out eventually because he writes about the times he's in, he's not relevant in the long-term.

Some would say Who's Next or maybe Tommy. Sorry, also dated and irrelevant. Should Bowie be a contender, with Low, or maybe Ziggy or Station To Station? Too many weak tracks.

In the end there are 3 albums that stand alone on top of the pile, timeless, musically impeccable, absolutely classic in all senses of the word, effortlessly gaining new fans generation after generation after generation.

For me, it's Exile. But I would argue against Revolver or IV.

posts.com:
Searching for music that sounds like these 5 tracks. It's difficult to describe exactly the feeling they give me but they are all marked by ambience, i.e. whatever rhythm and tempo they have is very slow and imperceptible, blending into the background, often irregular.

They create a sort of sonic landscape rather than 'tunes' and make regular use of maj7 and maj9 chords to create that sense of being open-ended, mysterious, evoking wonder.

All searches for 'ambient psychedelic guitar', or 'ambient new age guitar' have thus far been fruitless.

Hoping people here know the feeling and sound I'm talking about.

Super comfy, concise, and well-structured album. It works better than any other Floyd album as a coherent piece of art.

I'd just like to point out that my mom saw Rachmaninoff play when she was in high school and, while that only means that I'm an old fart, the mildly entertaining aspect of this is the reactions she got from her co-workers and peers in the '70s and '80s.

Mom was born in 1921 and her parents took her see him playing with the Cleveland Symphony sometime in the late '30s. When we moved to San Francisco in the early '70s (I was in high school then), we fell in with a group of younger coworkers at mom's law firm who were classical fans and we went to the winter Symphony concerts with them once in awhile. One show featured Piano Concerto #2, damned if I can recall who the soloist was. Anyway, mom mentioned in passing that she had seen him perform this very piece back when and her coworkers were simply stunned. So mom chided them a little about it and went with, "all that means is that I'm old". She was in her early '50s then, so clearly "not all that old" at all.

Thanks for following my blog don't forget to hit like and subscribe.

>>114862501
Proper technique reduces fatigue on your wrists and hands. In addition lots of practice will get you used to playing like that. If you're having trouble playing 16ths with one hand try out using both hands to play the 16th notes and modifying the sticking for the rest of the drums you need to play to accommodate. Although you'd be better off spending your time simply practicing and building your hand/arm endurance.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
I guess I've never thought about it. My biggest initial problem with 16th notes was getting my bass-foot on time (by this I mean playing kick rhythms freely along with a two-handed 16th technique, of course the kicks on the meter were easy).

I guess what built my stamina was playing a lot of white reggae like Sublime-style bands. This was before I realized most of those 16ths were being played one handed. I know the more comfortable you get two-handed, the more you can start having fun, like Stewart Copeland style hi-hat fun. That's what I would focus on is the accents and ruffs and whatnot. If you're having trouble one-handed, that's because that takes a lot of practice to get comfortable with. idk what Joy Division guy does, I don't listen to them.

I had stamina problems from like 14 to 16, but after I joined a punk band and had to keep up for 3-5 hours a session, those all melted away. I'm a fat old smoker and I could play for half the day if I wanted to. Eventually you find efficient motion.

>>114865904
>make your wrist and fingers do the work and not your arms
Disagree. Playing with wrists and fingers will make a different sound than punching it with your arms, those two things are equally important and needed in different situations. And you will discover that sometimes even when your wrist are dying, you can still play up to the tempo with your arms, because there are different muscles doing the the hard work then.
The most important thing for playing with arms though is the developing of grip and control over the punching, so you can feel where the sticks are and won't drop them.

An advanced well practiced player will prefer one handed 16th notes. It feels great, it sounds great, you burn a lot less energy and it’s just more fun imo. Sure if the tempo is blazing then one handed 16ths become impossible for most players including myself. I think the point of the OP was to inquire about how one goes about learning the proper technique to play quick groovy 16th with one hand.

My right hand is my week hand but I play right handed so I’ve spent hours, years working on my hh technique. Most players work on their left because it’s their weak hand. Finger, wrist and stick control exercises are the fundamentals

>>114881580
One hand is just better technique. Yes it takes a ton of practice to achieve said technique but it opens you up to a lot more possibilities. Ghost notes on the snare for example are harder and don’t sound as nice when you’re hacking at your hh with both hands. I used two hands when I was a beginner so I know where you’re at. Up tempo stuff still requires two hands for most guys. Like that joy division song. That drummer is mediocre at best and most guys playing that lick would need two hands.

If you’re not fast with your leading hand for 16th notes and have to use both hands then use both hands. But it’s bad technique.

third was judged completely differently because yes was infinitely more popular than the soft machine, because third came out in 1970 rather than 1973, and most importantly, because third was stylistically completely different from TfTO.
>the exact same thing
third was completely disjointed from the mainstream wankprog of ELP, yes, genesis and the like, and had nothing to do with the operatic, grandiose, sound and harmonic vocals singing about transcendent shit on TfTO
it's far more of a jazz-fusion album than anything else, and jazz had been getting albums with long pieces for a decade plus, so the (comparatively far smaller) was well prepared for an album of its kind
in the end, if TfTO was released by some small irrelevant band it would be well-beloved by now, but yes is the kind of band that you can ask a random 65 year old man about and they'd likely say "oh, I loved yours is no disgrace/starship trooper/i've seen all good people way back in the day when i was a kid!", and it was in the wrong place at the wrong time for critical reception

Learning to sample is alot of just doing it. There is not one way of sampling, there isnt some trick to learning what to listen for. Everything can be a sample given the right context. I've sampled everything from classical, jazz, hip hop, edm, film scores and death metal and grindcore.

I guess the only thing I can tell you about sampling is learning how to tempo match and figuring out the key of whatever you're sampling. You're also going to get very familiar with the limits of digital sound and aliasing so getting the highest available bitrate of whatever track you're sampling is also important.

Because sometimes you'll want to put certain effects / processing on one instrument and not others. Or you'll want to edit the patterns for a single instrument and leave the others alone. Also when you do more advanced compositions you'll sometimes have different instruments playing in the same range (though I don't recommend this unless you really know wtf you're doing) and keeping everything in one midi track will get confusing fast.

In orchestration there's a reason each instrument has its own staff on the sheet music, if every single performer were to play off the grand staff shit would be a clusterfuck.
